  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Karaoke Eternal Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Karaoke Eternal is a free, self-hosted karaoke party system with browser song queueing. See features, setup, pros, cons and alternatives for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Karaoke Eternal is a free and open-source, self-hosted karaoke party system that lets guests find and queue songs from their own phone's browser while a separate fullscreen player handles audio and video output for the room. The project is developed by a maintainer using the GitHub handle bhj and was previously named Karaoke Forever before being renamed Karaoke Eternal; it has no company, funding, or commercial edition behind it, and is supported purely through voluntary GitHub Sponsors contributions rather than a subscription business model. The software is architected around three cooperating components: a Server that runs on nearly any hardware, including a Raspberry Pi, a NAS device, or a Windows, Mac, or Linux desktop, and serves both the web application and the user's local media library; an App, which is a fast, modern mobile-optimized web interface designed specifically for the noisy, low-light conditions of an actual karaoke party, allowing guests to join a room via QR code, create a temporary guest account, and browse or search the song library on their own device; and a Player, meant to run fullscreen on the system connected to the room's speakers and screen, which handles audio and video playback plus WebGL-powered music-synced visualizations, including automatic lyrics background removal for a cleaner on-screen display. On the media side, Karaoke Eternal supports MP3+G files (the long-standing standard karaoke format pairing an MP3 audio track with a CDG graphics/lyrics file, including zipped variants) as well as standard MP4 video files, and it can host multiple simultaneous rooms, each with its own independent song queue and optional password protection, which makes it suitable for larger venues or events running more than one karaoke session at once. Because no microphones are wired into the software itself, the Player only handles music and on-screen lyrics output, leaving microphone amplification to the room's existing PA or speaker setup. Installation is available either as an official Docker image or as an npm package, both offered in multi-platform, multi-architecture builds requiring a 64-bit system, which keeps deployment straightforward for hobbyists already comfortable with self-hosted software. The project explicitly markets itself as having no ads and no telemetry, reinforcing its positioning within the privacy-respecting, self-hosted software community. Its target audience is hobbyists, bar and venue owners, and families or friend groups who want to run recurring karaoke nights without paying for commercial karaoke hosting services, jukebox subscriptions, or proprietary karaoke machines that lock users into specific song formats or licensing arrangements. Karaoke Eternal is frequently listed in self-hosted software directories such as Awesome-Selfhosted alongside other home entertainment server tools like Jellyfin and Navidrome, and its closest points of comparison are commercial karaoke party apps and standalone karaoke machines, as well as other lesser-known open-source karaoke queueing tools; Karaoke Eternal differentiates itself by requiring no dedicated hardware, working entirely through guests' own phone browsers with no app install, supporting multiple concurrent rooms out of the box, and remaining completely free with an actively maintained, ad-free, telemetry-free codebase.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '5ca6b722-6cdd-44cd-92f0-a9b94dd0cb9d';

